IV. Aliis aliarum. The Greek and Latin are both fond of a repetition of different cases of the same word, even where one of them is redundant, e. g. οἰόθεν οἶος (Hom. 11. ¹7, 39), and particu larly in the words ἄλλος and alius. Aliis is not however wholly redundant; but brings out more fully the idea : no intermarriayes, one with one nation, and another with another. Walch and Ritter omit aliis, though it is found in all the MSS.
